Mission.Title: Op Sand Scorpion - Part 1
Mission.Comments:
This initial strike on Russian forces in Syria has several objectives that must be fulfilled for it to be considered a success.
The 4 objectives are:
Destroy Mi-8s parked in Minakh airfield ========================= These helos are being used in offensive operations against civilians in areas unfriendly to the current regime. They represent a significant ground force component of region and their destruction will ensure that troop movement in temporarily restricted to vehicles only. This will help provide future targets of opportunity on Russian ground forces and restrict the range at which they can operate.
Destroy Ammunition and Fuel Dumps in Minakh ============================== Along with the destruction of helos at the airfield, the destruction of ammo and fuel dumps will further degrade Minakh airbase of being able to conduct offensive operations.
Destroy Supply Convoy En route to Minakh =========================== A convoy is en route from the main base of operations in Aleppo to Minakh. Convoy consists of 6 supply trucks carrying both ammunition and new pilots for helos based in Minakh.
Escort US Ambassador to Syria To US Forces =========================== The ambassador is currently vacationing in a beach side hotel in Lataki. Once offensive operations begin, it is highly likely that the ambassador will become a target of the regime. His security detail has been briefed and a LZ outside the hotel will be established for a US Naval helicopter to extract him and take him back to the Tarawa. There is light AAA presence in Lataki and there is the risk of small arms fire that a landing helo may attract as it approaches the city. Helos will require the removal of AAA in Lataki before they can approach the LZ.
It is expected that Russians will scramble air assets from Aleppo and Kuweires once Syrian border SAMs have been destroyed. Some element of counter air must be considered to protect strike aircraft on Minakh and hunting the convoy heading N from Aleppo.
